ut inline functions. My understanding is that while a callable reference to an inline function is acceptable, it appears to lose its inline property. I wonder about callable references specifically to reified type parameters — does that follow the same logic? It’s intriguing to think about how these nuances affect performance and type safety in Kotlin programming. I need to dig deeper into that to clarify!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_e8SH0kdnbLhOa0AVeDRV5OW6|fc_0f0689f477e11fa4016a3c8ce4ece48195b0bacddfbbbff4ba", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle /home/mihailo -name 'kotlin-stdlib*.jar' 2>/dev/null | head -5 | while read j; do echo $j; javap -classpath \"$j\" -c kotlin.jvm.internal.Intrinsics 2>/dev/null | grep -A8 \"reifiedOperationMarker\" && break; done", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1825, "output": 1542, "cacheRead": 49152, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 52519, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782353101674, "responseId": "resp_0f0689f477e11fa4016a3c8cce9c548195bd8a8d85140dcb7e"}}
